{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":92787,"duration_api_ms":92654,"num_turns":3,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"0d3b1fee-d086-46b2-8f57-e155040bb99d","total_cost_usd":0.29792505,"usage":{"input_tokens":4,"cache_creation_input_tokens":22330,"cache_read_input_tokens":75360,"output_tokens":1089,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":22330,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":4,"outputTokens":1089,"cacheReadInputTokens":75360,"cacheCreationInputTokens":22330,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.20448750000000002,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000},"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":57,"outputTokens":4063,"cacheReadInputTokens":207843,"cacheCreationInputTokens":41825,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.09343755000000001,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"Evaluated three amendments against the actual code in fs.rs and model.rs. Amendment fr-9-ed4ab282 identifies a real defensive gap worth addressing. Amendment fr-9-b6508003 raises a valid future-proofing concern. Amendment fr-9-05edcb4b is based on a factual misunderstanding of the code.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-9-ed4ab282","decision":"accept","rationale":"The amendment correctly identifies that the function signature permits (Some(run_id), None) for requested_started_at, which would cause the started_at guard (lines 2823-2828) to be skipped entirely for runless terminal candidates. Currently the only call site passing None for both parameters is safe, but the function's contract is implicit. A debug_assert!(requested_run_id.is_none() || requested_started_at.is_some()) or equivalent guard is a low-cost, high-value defensive measure that would catch misuse immediately rather than silently backfilling the wrong terminal row. This is a legitimate invariant enforcement issue."},{"amendment_id":"fr-9-b6508003","decision":"accept","rationale":"The amendment correctly identifies that json_fill_none relies on the interaction between or_insert (only fills absent keys) and skip_serializing_if (omits None fields so keys are absent). If a future Option field is added without skip_serializing_if, it would serialize as null, the key would be present, and or_insert would not fill it from the overlay. The existing structs (StartJournalDetails, CompletionJournalDetails) correctly use #[serde(default, skip_serializing_if = \"Option::is_none\")] on all Option fields, but this implicit coupling is fragile. Adding a test that verifies the fill behavior and a doc-comment on the structs requiring the serde attributes on all Option fields is a sound defensive measure with minimal cost."},{"amendment_id":"fr-9-05edcb4b","decision":"reject","rationale":"The amendment's concern is based on a misunderstanding. The outcome field in CompletionJournalDetails is typed as String, not TaskRunOutcome. Values stored in this field come from TaskRunOutcome::Display, which produces deterministic lowercase strings ('succeeded', 'failed', 'skipped', etc.), and TaskRunOutcome also uses #[serde(rename_all = \"snake_case\")] ensuring canonical serialization. The string comparison at line 2374 (existing.outcome != requested.outcome) is correct because both sides originate from the same Display or serde path, producing identical strings for identical outcomes. There is no realistic scenario where the same logical outcome would produce different string representations. Adding a test for Display canonicity would be harmless but addresses a non-existent risk — the enum's Display impl is already trivially deterministic by inspection."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"65f789bb-aaf7-4be8-ae0d-941e81f46f52"}
